Part 6

I didn't know any of this when it happened.

Vikram never told me the board meeting story, or the window, or Ira Sen's name, not once, not even later when we were old men and had run out of things to hide from each other.

I pieced it together the way you piece together most of a friend's life you weren't present for — from a line here, a name mentioned once and never again, a nurse's file, an old employee who still remembered "Ahuja Sahib" fondly enough to talk.

Some of it I'm still guessing at. I'll say so when I am.

What I do know, because he told me this part directly, once, sitting outside the ICU with two cold cups of tea neither of us drank:

"I never wanted the business, Adarsh. Twice life decided for me. Not once."

I asked what he meant by twice.

"1996. Then 2007. My father's liver, both times. First time it let go of him a little. Second time it didn't."

He didn't explain further, and I didn't ask him to. Some men tell you a fact and expect you to sit with it, not chase it.

I sat with it for years before I understood what he meant.

Two times, a decade apart, the same door opened and pulled him out of a life he'd actually chosen — a stethoscope, a hostel room, a friend, me — and put him behind a desk he hadn't asked for.

Most men would have called that unfair and stopped there.

Vikram didn't run either time.

I know that much for certain, because I watched what came after, even the parts I didn't understand until much later.

That was the board meeting.

That was the window.

That, I would learn only after his death, was also Ira Sen, whose name he mentioned to me exactly once in fifty years, and only in passing, as if checking that the wound was still there before moving on.

But that was only the beginning.

The real test came next.
